[{"id":30260,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>Br</mi><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow></msub><mo>;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>-</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow></msub><mo>;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>Br</mi><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow></msub><mo>;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>Br</mi><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>Br</mi><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>-</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow></msub><mo>;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>Br</mi><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>Br</mi><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi><mo>)</mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>Br</mi><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow></msub><mo>;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>-</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow></msub><mo>;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>Br</mi><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow></msub><mo>;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>Br</mi><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>Br</mi><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow></msub><mo>;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>-</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow></msub><mo>;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>Br</mi><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow></msub><mo>;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>Br</mi><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow></msub></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<blockquote><p>The leaving group which results in the formation of more stable carbocation will be more reactive towards S<sub>N</sub>1 reaction.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/6f06b262-7155-41aa-bb1a-4ab072dca3c0.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 146px;\" /></p><p>In the above molecule, by leaving of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Br</mi><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow></msub></math>&nbsp;benzyl carbocation is formed. Benzyl carbocation is more stable than aliphatic carbocation.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/bc464402-0744-4ff9-8362-3e7ce7134916.png\" style=\"width: 250px; height: 54px;\" /></p><p>By replacing&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow></msub></math>&nbsp;in the above molecule, allyl carbocation is formed. Allyl carbocation is more stable than aliphatic carbocation.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/5c8d8b32-a2b3-4f7e-9539-485e2c0c12bf.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 150px;\" /></p><p>In the above molecule, it is difficult to replace&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Br</mi><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow></msub></math>, as carbocation formed at bridge head position is very difficult. Hence,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Br</mi><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow></msub></math>&nbsp;is more reactive.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/06c7a3e2-2c93-4164-9a46-4431a3814ecb.png\" style=\"width: 218px; height: 108px;\" /></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Br</mi><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow></msub></math>&nbsp;is more reactive than&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Br</mi><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow></msub></math>&nbsp;in the above molecule, because tertiary carbocation is more stable than primary carbocation.</p><p>Hence, the correct answer is option (3).</p><p>&nbsp;</p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (08 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30292,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/459068c6-f9ec-4357-8361-8bd89d7be48d-image.png\" style=\"width: 252px; height: 124px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ed179de9-5f8f-4bd2-8b02-a41a2aaac267-image.png\" style=\"width: 326px; height: 126px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ff534888-f22b-461d-85b2-71e6a06e2595-image.png\" style=\"width: 151px; height: 151px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/2169fa6c-b4f4-4c45-879e-536e34700c00-image.png\" style=\"width: 146px; height: 148px;\" />"],"answer":2,"solution":"<blockquote><p>According to the question, In the first step of the reaction, when cyclo-pentyl-chloride reacts with magnesium in the presence of dry ether than cyclo-pentyl-magnesium-chloride (grignard reagent) is formed.&nbsp;</p><p>In the second step of the reaction, when grignard reagent is react with a compound, which has active hydrogen than grignard reagent abstract hydrogen from&nbsp;active hydrogen compound and converted in to alkane.&nbsp;</p><p>So cyclo-pentane is formed as the product(second step of the reaction) of this reaction.&nbsp;</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/3945a8a7-cdad-4dd7-956f-53ce630b91f6-image.png\" style=\"width: 576px; height: 94px;\" /></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (27 Aug Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30255,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["A-III, B-I, C-IV, D-II","A-I, B-II, C-III, D-IV","A-I, B-III, C-IV, D-II","A-IV, B-III, C-II, D-I"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>(A) When <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>-</mo></math>bromopropane&nbsp;reacts&nbsp;with alcoholic<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>KOH</mi></math>,&nbsp;the bromine with the alpha H (hydrogen from the carbon alongside the carbon fortified with useful gathering) is eliminated and subsequently forms <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>-</mo></math>propene.&nbsp;<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/af89f5c7-a461-4945-8f7d-271ad15a79f9.png\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 61px;\" /></p><p>(B) When&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>-</mo></math>Bromo propane reacts with&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>alc</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>KCN</mi></math>&nbsp;it will form butanenitrile.&nbsp;</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/f5e4c9d5-301c-4f08-acfc-26ebbdaaee6e.png\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 63px;\" /></p><p>(C)&nbsp; When akyl halide reacts with silver nitrite, nitroalkane is formed because&nbsp;the bond between <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Ag</mi><mo>&#8722;</mo><mi>OAg</mi><mo>&#8722;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></math>&nbsp;is covalent, the lone pair on nitrogen acts as an attacking site for nucleophilic substitution.&nbsp;&nbsp;<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/4d950621-18cc-4e64-bf3b-d96e81fbabf9.png\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 80px;\" /></p><p>(D)&nbsp;When <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>-</mo></math>bromopropane reacts with silver acetate, propyl ethanoate and silver bromide are formed.<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/bf11b6d8-cd01-408d-9650-69d11993fb7d.png\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 85px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (13 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30341,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["<math><mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">F</mi></mrow><mo>/</mo><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">u</mi></mrow></mrow></math>","<math><mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">u</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></mrow><mo>/</mo><mrow><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></mrow></mrow></math>","Only Heat","<math><mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub></mrow><mo>/</mo><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">u</mi></mrow></mrow></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"Only Heat<br /><br /><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/d66a2f43-72b5-4283-8bbc-29d80c864eb0-image.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 116px;\" />","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2016 (10 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":30321,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/277169fd-1817-42af-82d8-37bec8aca84a-image.png\" style=\"width: 169px; height: 78px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/8c6ee5ad-ef39-46ff-893d-2a768f8a19b9-image22.png\" style=\"width: 169px; height: 120px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/a6363d97-72b8-48d7-9bfc-0cb951f3f0cb-image23.png\" style=\"width: 169px; height: 90px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/c1afe4af-6c31-4ebb-9384-984df93f7bf4-image24.png\" style=\"width: 169px; height: 117px;\" />"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">E</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math>&nbsp;reaction is a single step reaction in which a strong base is used to attack on the reactant for removing leaving group. Now Alkene is formed. Now proton attacks&nbsp;on carbonyl compound to form carbocation which later shows freidel&nbsp;craft acylation reaction.</p><p>As shown below:</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/e118107f-d335-4c6d-bb34-c8867d03719f-image.png\" style=\"width: 600px; height: 390px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (08 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30297,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>HCl</mi></math>;&nbsp;Anhydrous <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>AlCl</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>HCl</mi><mo>,</mo><msub><mi>ZnCl</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>Cl</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>UV</mi></math> light","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>Cl</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>; dark, Anhydrous <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>AlCl</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/f73cdf5b-44cd-415c-ae54-332973a028f1-image.png\" style=\"width: 230px; height: 162px;\" /></p><p>For substitution at allylic position in the given compound, the reagent used is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Cl</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>/</mo><mi>UV</mi></math>&nbsp;light.</p><p>The reaction is free radical halogenation.&nbsp;</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/829c25fd-b5c1-4d24-bc5c-c663f5158a4c-image.png\" style=\"width: 261px; height: 164px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (16 Mar Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30327,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["<p><img height=\"93\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/9dea5a8c-18ad-49b8-ba69-8f89a85554ff-image.png\" width=\"218\" /></p>","<p><img height=\"114\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/7235e85f-309c-4ca3-9c53-fdc419cfe15f-image.png\" width=\"261\" /></p>","<p><img height=\"144\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/11d91ee4-def1-46e9-976c-7c266ab3f333-image.png\" width=\"175\" /></p>","<p><img height=\"134\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/4c56a901-f136-4583-a537-f3c306bc6e42-image.png\" width=\"198\" /></p>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ab7b7001-1ed1-46f9-8395-59f7583a0402-image.png\" style=\"width: 628px; height: 154px;\" /></p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/6536322c-524a-4f14-9b96-584082441df9-image.png\" style=\"width: 628px; height: 88px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (10 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30247,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["Statement I is true but Statement II is false.","Statement I is false but Statement II is true.","Both statement I and Statement II are false.","Both statement I and Statement II are true."],"answer":3,"solution":"<blockquote><p>Statement - I: Rate of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></msub><mn>2</mn><mo>∝</mo><mo>[</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi><mo>]</mo><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><msup><mi>Nu</mi><mo>-</mo></msup></mfenced></math><br/><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></msub><mn>2</mn></math> reaction is favoured by high concentration of nucleophile <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><msup><mi>Nu</mi><mo>-</mo></msup></mfenced><mo>&amp;</mo></math> less crowding in the substrate molecule.</p><h2><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></msub><mn>2</mn></math> Reaction Mechanism</h2><p>This reaction proceeds through a backside attack by the nucleophile on the substrate. The nucleophile approaches the given substrate at an angle of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mn>180</mn><mo>°</mo></msup></math> to the carbon-leaving group bond. The carbon-nucleophile bond forms and carbon-leaving group <em>bond breaks </em>simultaneously through a transition state.</p><p>Now, the leaving group is pushed out of the transition state on the opposite side of the carbon-nucleophile bond, forming the required product. It is important to note that the <em>product is formed with an inversion of the tetrahedral geometry at the atom in the centre.</em></p><p>Statement - II: Solvolysis follows <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></msub><mn>1</mn></math> path.</p><p>he <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></msub><mn>1</mn></math> reaction is a nucleophilic substitution reaction where the rate-determining step is unimolecular. It is a type of organic substitution reaction. <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></msub><mn>1</mn></math> stands for substitution nucleophilic unimolecular. Thus, the rate equation (which states that the <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></msub><mn>1</mn></math> reaction is dependent on the electrophile but not on the nucleophile) holds in situations where the amount of the nucleophile is far greater than the amount of the carbocation intermediate.</p><p>This reaction involves the formation of a carbocation intermediate. It is generally seen in the reactions of tertiary or secondary alkyl halides with secondary or tertiary alcohols under strongly acidic or strongly basic conditions. The <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></msub><mn>1</mn></math> reaction is often referred to as the dissociative mechanism in inorganic chemistry.</p><p>Both are correct statements.</p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (30 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30231,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["Both Statement I and Statement II are incorrect","Both Statement I and Statement II are correct","Statement I is incorrect but Statement II is correct","Statement I is correct but Statement II is incorrect"],"answer":1,"solution":"Both statement-I and statement-II are correct\nStatement - I: $\\mathrm{CH}_3-\\mathrm{O}-\\stackrel{\\oplus}{\\mathrm{C}} \\mathrm{H}_2$ is highly stable carbocation.\n\nStatement - II: Due to hindrance, $\\mathrm{S}_{\\mathrm{N}} 2$ will not take place easily.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (22 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30285,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["benzyl bromide","bromobenzene","cyclohexyl bromide","methyl bromide"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/21f8d8ea-1827-453e-9f2e-603493e13952-image.png\" style=\"width: 550px; height: 157px;\" /></p><p>A is bromobenzene which forms phenyl magnesium bromide(grignard reagent) with magnesium in presence of THF.</p><p>2 moles of Phenyl magnesium bromide on reaction with methyl benzoate&nbsp; followed by hydrolysis forms a tertiary alcohol.</p><p>&nbsp;</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (25 Jun Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30344,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["<img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/38f43d39-1626-4c1a-a86a-c1cd087d8a54-11.png\" style=\"width: 120px; height: 127px;\" />","<img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/af670c8b-96df-42ab-bc18-b0cbee9f4c75-22.png\" style=\"width: 120px; height: 132px;\" />","<img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/b594aea4-5141-4feb-9ae1-1599de8985db-33.png\" style=\"width: 150px; height: 115px;\" />","<img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/2a940e2f-220c-43a2-bfb9-accb15dc43ed-44.png\" style=\"width: 120px; height: 120px;\" />"],"answer":3,"solution":"<img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/c91f6571-a1e3-4949-9045-5d696296bde0-nbss.png\" style=\"width: 536px; height: 398px;\" />","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2016 (03 Apr)","image":null},{"id":30310,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/a1077b33-a548-4169-af02-c7412d3f693a.jpeg\">","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/cdd7747f-e7f4-4747-b2d4-344f1673829a.jpeg\">","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/d6813795-5d81-47af-ac05-05873fb31535.jpeg\">","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/844ad08c-c108-4e3f-ac69-b4bb127a61fd.jpeg\">"],"answer":1,"solution":"Aniline forms&nbsp;anilinium complex with Lewis acid, so phenol is most reactive among the given compounds for electrophilic substitution reaction.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (09 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30273,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Benzylic and tertiary carbocations are stable. The positive charge is unstable at double bonded carbon. Hence, two moles of silver chloride is precipitated from one mole of given molecule.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/50a85a70-b5f6-4e5e-9ccf-be2511e246d3-image.png\" style=\"width: 308px; height: 147px;\" /></p><p>In the above molecule, carbon-1 and carbo-2 are double bonded carbons. Carbon-3 and carbon-4 forms secondary carbocation and tertiary carbocation respectively.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (24 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30221,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["(A)-(III), (B)-(II), (C)-(IV), (D)-(I)","(A)-(III), (B)-(IV), (C)-(II), (D)-(I)","(A)-(IV), (B)-(III), (C)-(I), (D)-(II)","(A)-(IV), (B)-(I), (C)-(II), (D)-(III)"],"answer":1,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/xaSWrS0BfB9bBqWrjy8L5KgN5cYS4Hoa4g_g41ngWDY.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (2 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30212,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["III $<$ I $<$ II $<$ IV","IV $<$ III $<$ II $<$ I","I $<$ II $<$ III $<$ IV","II $<$ I $<$ III $<$ IV"],"answer":3,"solution":"Rate of $S_N1 \\propto$ Stability of $C^{\\oplus}$ formed<br>(I) and (II) are unstable due to Bredt's rule, (I) has more +I effect.<br>(II) < (I) < (III) < (IV)","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (22 January Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30360,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/4dmjrEJ9NmlxRJnRfGvbYOvQi3ta7sjwStPT2WCpB8A.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/i8cwGF9sBGhZYF-nhx5PQmBwTe6XaLN6xlsDIBFrf6I.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/yGr1TzejoHsAJIj5HfJgNVB84Bt9ceEl5Og7x678fnA.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/FtY55OxKZ2bwlxLAClltZWDkfk5c5XRgJYH4rJNeySQ.original.fullsize.png\"><br>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/00p8gI9_7uQnMAVtn6s8wgWR7J0D_pmkScH87VIoae4.original.fullsize.png\"><br>\n(Since tertiary carbocation is more stable)","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2013 (09 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":30233,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["(A) is correct but (R) is not correct","(A) is not correct but (R) is correct","Both (A) and (R) are correct but (R) is not the correct explanation of (A)","Both (A) and (R) are correct and (R) is the correct explanation of \\((\\mathbf{A})\\)"],"answer":3,"solution":"The benzyl group acts in much the same way using the $\\pi$-system of the benzene ring for conjugation with the p-orbital in the transition state.\n<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/m8rQlDMHHbuRDtQyRorWvRKt73B3lUOzUL4zqOyToAU.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (09 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30199,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["Both Statement I and Statement II are true","Both Statement I and Statement II are false","Statement I is true but Statement II is false","Statement I is false but Statement II is true"],"answer":0,"solution":"Statement I is true because as the size of the alkyl group increases, the molecular mass and surface area increase. This leads to an increase in the magnitude of van der Waals forces, which in turn increases the boiling point. Thus, the correct order of boiling points is $\\text{CH}_3\\text{CH}_2\\text{CH}_2\\text{I} > \\text{CH}_3\\text{CH}_2\\text{I} > \\text{CH}_3\\text{I}$.<br><br>Statement II is true because para-dichlorobenzene is more symmetrical than ortho-dichlorobenzene, allowing it to pack more efficiently in the crystal lattice, which results in a higher melting point. However, ortho-dichlorobenzene has a higher dipole moment than para-dichlorobenzene (which has a dipole moment of zero). The stronger dipole-dipole interactions in ortho-dichlorobenzene lead to a higher boiling point compared to para-dichlorobenzene.<br><br>Both Statement I and Statement II are true.<br><br>Answer: Both Statement I and Statement II are true","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (08 April Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30269,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["(B), (C) and (D) only","(A), (C) and (E) only","(A), (C) and (D) only","(A), (B) and (E) only"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>The boiling point of organic compounds depends on two factors:</p><p>(i) Molecular weight: Boiling point increases with increase in molecular weight.</p><p>(ii) Intermolecular forces: Higher the strength of intermolecular forces, higher is the boiling point.</p><p>As the mass of the compound increases then their boiling point will also increase. Hence, (A) and (C) are correct.</p><p>Density of Et-Cl = 0.89 g/ml</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Et-Br = 1.47 g/ml</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Et-I = 1.94 g/ml</p><p>Density of halides increases with number of carbon atoms and at mass of halogen present. So, (B) and (D) is incorrect.</p><p>As branching of the compound increases then boiling point decreases. Hence, (E) is correct.</p><p>So, the correct answer is (A), (C) and (E) only.</p><p>&nbsp;</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (29 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30366,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/VroeQvyYPMbCmAjHsn5kxLxOasV9oHJkdCkJshJTiAs.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/rc_9v8V36HIiFbmMtuBpWvprBMcw1Uj379qIK_6q9Go.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/xdadLpUXc_qKJFAugzzwJ8lgSnmCR4870MfQI3t__zE.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/SpZGLwTvpK9FLHGgoSSow4IY6g4K2tRtyp8S1Vhzg2o.original.fullsize.png\"><br>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/yohKBF7N4QD9gc_ti70kH8obC2j1fq3wplVdlBFqdOw.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2012 (12 May Online)","image":null},{"id":30214,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["$\\mathrm{I}^{-}>\\mathrm{C}_{2} \\mathrm{H}_{5} \\mathrm{O}^{-}>\\mathrm{F}^{-}>\\mathrm{C}_{6} \\mathrm{H}_{5} \\mathrm{O}^{-}$","$\\mathrm{I}^{-}>\\mathrm{C}_{2} \\mathrm{H}_{5} \\mathrm{O}^{-}>\\mathrm{C}_{6} \\mathrm{H}_{5} \\mathrm{O}^{-}>\\mathrm{F}^{-}$","$\\mathrm{I}^{-}>\\mathrm{F}^{-}>\\mathrm{C}_{6} \\mathrm{H}_{5} \\mathrm{O}^{-}>\\mathrm{C}_{2} \\mathrm{H}_{5} \\mathrm{O}^{-}$","$\\mathrm{I}^{-}>\\mathrm{C}_{6} \\mathrm{H}_{5} \\mathrm{O}^{-}>\\mathrm{F}^{-}>\\mathrm{C}_{2} \\mathrm{H}_{5} \\mathrm{O}^{-}$"],"answer":1,"solution":"In methanol (protic solvent), nucleophilicity is determined by basicity and solvation effects. Smaller ions are heavily solvated by the protic solvent, reducing their effective nucleophilicity.<br><br>C₂H₅O⁻ (ethoxide) is the strongest nucleophile as it is less solvated and highly basic.<br><br>C₆H₅O⁻ (phenoxide) is weaker due to resonance stabilization by the benzene ring.<br><br>F⁻ is highly solvated despite high basicity, reducing its nucleophilicity significantly.<br><br>I⁻ is the best nucleophile because it is the largest ion and least solvated in methanol.<br><br>The correct order is I⁻ > C₂H₅O⁻ > C₆H₅O⁻ > F⁻.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (22 January Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30268,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn></math>-Bromo-<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math>-methylbutane","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math>-Bromopropane","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math>-Bromopentane","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math>-Bromo-<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn></math>, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn></math>-dimethylpentane"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>In dehydrohalogenation reactions,&nbsp;the preferred product is that alkene which has the greater number of alkyl groups attached to the doubly bonded carbon atoms. Thus, 2-bromopentane gives pent-2-ene as the major product.</p><p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/83488d5f-42a2-4f47-9bed-c1a7ad154c16-7fc755fa-a43e-49f8-9496-f41827617b4f-a44d5f49-5106-4827-8a0f-ce21c19634a1-image.png\" style=\"width: 446px; height: 103px;\" />Rest all bromides are having only one type of beta hydrogen, hence, only one possible alkene is formed.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (29 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30355,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["It is a covalent molecule.","It contains <math> <mrow> <msup> <mtext>Cs</mtext> <mo>+</mo> </msup> </mrow> </math> and <math> <mrow> <msubsup> <mtext>I</mtext> <mn>3</mn> <mo>-</mo> </msubsup> </mrow> </math> ions.","It contains <math> <mrow> <msup> <mtext>Cs</mtext> <mrow> <mn>3</mn> <mo>+</mo> </mrow> </msup> </mrow> </math> and <math> <mrow> <msup> <mtext>I</mtext> <mrow> <mo>-</mo> </mrow> </msup> </mrow> </math> ions.","It contains <math> <mrow> <msup> <mtext>Cs</mtext> <mo>+</mo> </msup> <msup> <mo>, I</mo> <mo>-</mo> </msup> </mrow> </math> and lattice <math> <mrow> <msub> <mtext>I</mtext> <mn>2</mn> </msub> </mrow> </math> molecule."],"answer":1,"solution":"<math> <mrow> <msubsup> <mtext>I</mtext> <mn>3</mn> <mo>-</mo> </msubsup> </mrow> </math> ion is made by the addition of excess iodine to iodide solution.<br /><br /><math> <mrow> <msub> <mtext>I</mtext> <mn>2</mn> </msub> <mo>+</mo> <msup> <mtext>I</mtext> <mo>-</mo> </msup> <mo>→</mo> <msubsup> <mtext>I</mtext> <mn>3</mn> <mo>-</mo> </msubsup> </mrow> </math><br /><br />Cs will always be in +1 oxidation state.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2014 (06 Apr)","image":null},{"id":30281,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/c055f8c6-cc40-4c0e-83b1-82c48a4980f3-image.png\" style=\"width: 120px; height: 169px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/3b299a74-14d6-4269-88f7-fd890e5b6255-image.png\" style=\"width: 90px; height: 136px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/86abd234-f6c6-4c6d-83a9-a55ccd3aeeb9-image.png\" style=\"width: 90px; height: 173px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/79d8dc36-879a-4022-bc00-e1a90195b914-jeeq.png\" style=\"width: 180px; height: 74px;\" /></p>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>4-bromotoluene undergoes free radical chlorination,to form 4-bromo benzyl chloride.</p><p>4-bromo benzyl chloride on reaction with KCN from</p><p>&nbsp;4-Bromobenzyl Cyanide which undergoes hydrolysis to form&nbsp;4-Bromophenyl acetic acid,</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/f72586c6-acd8-47fd-b19c-3994695dfb5a-a2acecf4-8f6d-4f55-8506-4f2010a2d96c-image.png\" style=\"width: 440px; height: 119px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (28 Jun Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30305,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/48a43ef4-ebf9-404b-a35b-b3a2a59ba4ab-image.png\" style=\"width: 99px; height: 75px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/87a73b1e-469c-4c7b-b975-c1c8e043c19a-image.png\" style=\"width: 122px; height: 73px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ee61d0a5-5bc6-4e20-bcd8-f88139069a6d-image.png\" style=\"width: 94px; height: 66px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/1ec08f5b-0a60-449b-a237-f860d94d14e8-image.png\" style=\"width: 133px; height: 87px;\" />"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/47c9ff36-e61e-4923-bed1-1cc7c1ffb529-image.png\" style=\"width: 812px; height: 91px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (03 Sep Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30371,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["$\\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{COCl}$","$\\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{CH}_2 \\mathrm{Cl}$","$\\mathrm{CH}_2 \\mathrm{Cl} \\mathrm{CH}_2 \\mathrm{Cl}$","$\\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{CHCl}_2$"],"answer":3,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/MbdULqAygWQlup3ZOzWNwCw7dshEemqdpAqPjZixZdQ.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2009","image":null},{"id":30201,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["A and B Only","A and C Only","B and D Only","D and E Only"],"answer":0,"solution":"Reaction A: $C_6H_5CH_2Br + AgCN \\rightarrow C_6H_5CH_2NC + AgBr$<br>$AgCN$ is predominantly covalent, so the nucleophilic attack occurs through the nitrogen atom, forming benzyl isocyanide.<br><br>Reaction B: $C_6H_5CH_2NH_2 + CHCl_3 + 3NaOH \\rightarrow C_6H_5CH_2NC + 3NaCl + 3H_2O$<br>This is the carbylamine reaction. Primary amines react with chloroform and alkali to form isocyanides. Benzyl amine gives benzyl isocyanide.<br><br>Reaction C: $C_6H_5Br + AgCN \\rightarrow$ No reaction<br>Aryl halides are generally unreactive towards nucleophilic substitution under normal conditions due to the partial double bond character of the C-Br bond.<br><br>Reaction D: $C_6H_5NH_2 + CHCl_3 + 3NaOH \\rightarrow C_6H_5NC + 3NaCl + 3H_2O$<br>Aniline undergoes the carbylamine reaction to form phenyl isocyanide, not benzyl isocyanide.<br><br>Reaction E: $C_6H_5CH_2CH_2Br + KCN \\rightarrow C_6H_5CH_2CH_2CN + KBr$<br>$KCN$ is predominantly ionic, so the nucleophilic attack occurs through the carbon atom, forming a cyanide (nitrile) rather than an isocyanide.<br><br>Thus, benzyl isocyanide is obtained from reactions A and B only.<br><br>Answer: A and B Only","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (05 April Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30257,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/68c4edb9-e89f-45d1-8e62-19a6008f8671.png\" style=\"width: 250px; height: 165px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/28de690a-987c-4c32-888b-08c1426fd418.png\" style=\"width: 350px; height: 139px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/5231deda-e751-4ce8-a28d-8434ee9c2018.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 168px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/604495e9-cbc6-4fdb-af6d-68d8d3dcb595.png\" style=\"width: 250px; height: 106px;\" />"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Friedel-Crafts Alkylation refers to the replacement of an aromatic proton with an alkyl group. This is done through an electrophilic attack on the aromatic ring with the help of a carbocation generated from the alkyl halide and Lewis acid aluminium chloride. In the given case ring closure reaction takes place and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>OCH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math> is ortho/para directing, major product will be obtained from para attack.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/5efe8fc5-89be-437d-82d7-2499d824c2a0.png\" style=\"width: 500px; height: 152px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (10 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30368,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["Tertiary butyl chloride","Neopentane","Isohexane","Neohexane"],"answer":1,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/Lh7j7HIV2ttY20QQaX_izmT2pcLtTP10gdOocDurhvo.original.fullsize.png\"><br>\nMol. wt $=72 ~u$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2012 (Offline)","image":null},{"id":30379,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["4-phenylcyclopentene","2-phenylcyclopentene","1-phenylcyclopentene","3-phenylcyclopentene"],"answer":3,"solution":"According to ${E}_2$ mechanism.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2006","image":null},{"id":30275,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/f8fedb5c-1212-4b5c-996a-fd59f6d0f958-image.png\" style=\"width: 254px; height: 40px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/20a83a95-d9f8-4759-bedc-cbcbcb0868d5-image.png\" style=\"width: 254px; height: 40px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/e766ceba-526f-4c84-8234-161c2a0bbaf2-image.png\" style=\"width: 285px; height: 45px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/a3013555-ce98-472f-bda5-0dce4e971058-image.png\" style=\"width: 277px; height: 45px;\" /></p>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<blockquote><p>Groups like cyanides and nitrites possess two nucleophilic centres and are called ambident nucleophiles. Actually cyanide group is a hybrid of two contributing structures and therefore can act as a nucleophile in two different ways <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mo>[</mo><mo>-</mo></msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>&#8801;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#8596;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>:</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>=</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mo>-</mo></msup><mo>]</mo></math>, i.e., linking through carbon atom resulting in alkyl cyanides and through nitrogen atom leading to isocyanides.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/4f92421c-6d12-43bd-af50-6913177e8195-image.png\" style=\"width: 372px; height: 120px;\" /></p><p>KCN is predominantly ionic and provides cyanide ions in solution. Although both carbon and nitrogen atoms are in a position to donate electron pairs, the attack takes place mainly through carbon atom and not through nitrogen atom since C&mdash;C bond is more stable than C&mdash;N bond. However, AgCN is mainly covalent in nature and nitrogen is free to donate electron pair forming isocyanide as the main product.</p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (29 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30386,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["gammexene","hexachloroethane","Freon","DDT"],"answer":3,"solution":"No Solution Available","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2004","image":null},{"id":30372,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["$\\left(\\mathrm{C}_2 \\mathrm{H}_5\\right)_2 \\mathrm{CHCl}$","$\\left(\\mathrm{CH}_3\\right)_3 \\mathrm{CCl}$","$\\left(\\mathrm{CH}_3\\right)_2 \\mathrm{CHCl}$","$\\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{Cl}$"],"answer":3,"solution":"For $\\mathrm{S}_{\\mathrm{N}} 2$ reaction, the $\\mathrm{C}$ atom is least hindered towards the attack of nucleophile in the case of $\\left(\\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{Cl}\\right)$.\nHence, (D) is the correct answer.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2008","image":null},{"id":30328,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["<p><img height=\"103\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/f50acf26-f7b2-4320-9525-a466c38da08b-image.png\" width=\"154\" /></p>","<p><img height=\"99\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/cbd3d403-76d9-4483-a1e0-066352d1c001-image.png\" width=\"116\" /></p>","<p><img height=\"93\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/d38776c6-ade5-4ad4-96cb-bb4ee60b6cc9-image.png\" width=\"142\" /></p>","<p><img height=\"95\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/66fd3b2a-7b7e-494f-9d51-186a67d1885c-image.png\" width=\"135\" /></p>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>The first step is anti addition of <math><msub><mrow><mi>B</mi><mi>r</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub></math> across the double bond.<br /><br /><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/7a45c302-0d57-4092-b3f1-10134ea6095f-qweaa.png\" style=\"width: 372px; height: 115px;\" /><br /><br />In the second step, <math><mi>E</mi><mi>t</mi><msup><mrow><mi>O</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo></mrow></msup></math> <math><mo>(</mo><mi>n</mi><msup><mrow><mi>u</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo></mrow></msup></math> ) gets added by <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></msub><mn>1</mn></math> mechanism. And <math><mi>B</mi><msup><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo></mrow></msup></math> from the dashed position acts as the leaving group leads to the formation of a stable benzylic carbocation.<br /><br /><img height=\"107\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/1cc0e7fd-0196-435c-8de4-0b978ced6064-image.png\" width=\"349\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (09 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30312,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["<math><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#956;</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mrow></msub><mo>&#62;</mo><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#956;</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mrow></msub></math> <em>and</em> <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">k</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi></msub><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mfenced><mo>&#62;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">k</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi></msub><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mfenced></math>","<math><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">μ</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mrow></msub><mo>&gt;</mo><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">μ</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mrow></msub></math> <em>and</em> <math><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">k</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi></mrow></msub><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>&gt;</mo><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">k</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi></mrow></msub><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mrow></mfenced></math>","<math><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">μ</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mrow></msub><mo>&gt;</mo><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">μ</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mrow></msub></math> <em>and</em> <math><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">k</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi></mrow></msub><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>&gt;</mo><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">k</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi></mrow></msub><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mrow></mfenced></math>","<math><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">μ</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mrow></msub><mo>&gt;</mo><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">μ</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mrow></msub></math> <em>and</em> <math><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">k</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi></mrow></msub><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>&gt;</mo><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">k</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi></mrow></msub><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mrow></mfenced></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/c68e1dd3-1d53-4699-82e5-e02ebb2e9484-image.png\" style=\"width: 457px; height: 212px;\" /><br /><br />(B) with more steric crowding forms elimination product compared to substitution<br /><br /><math> <mrow> <msub> <mtext>K</mtext> <mtext>e</mtext> </msub> <mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mtext>B</mtext><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>&#62;</mo><msub> <mtext>K</mtext> <mtext>e</mtext> </msub> <mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mtext>A</mtext><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mtext>&#8201;</mtext><msub> <mi>&#956;</mi> <mtext>B</mtext> </msub> <mo>=</mo><mfrac> <mrow> <msub> <mtext>K</mtext> <mtext>s</mtext> </msub> <mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mtext>B</mtext><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow> <mrow> <msub> <mtext>K</mtext> <mtext>e</mtext> </msub> <mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mtext>A</mtext><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow> </mfrac> <mo>&#60;</mo><msub> <mi>&#956;</mi> <mtext>A</mtext> </msub> <mo>=</mo><mfrac> <mrow> <msub> <mtext>K</mtext> <mtext>s</mtext> </msub> <mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mtext>A</mtext><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow> <mrow> <msub> <mtext>K</mtext> <mtext>e</mtext> </msub> <mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mtext>A</mtext><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow> </mfrac> </mrow> </math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (07 Jan Shift 2)","image":null}]